{"title_page": "Anders Tegnell", "text_new": "{{short description|Swedish physician and civil servant}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Anders Tegnell\n|image              = \n|office             = State [[Epidemiologist]] of the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]]\n|term_start         = 2013\n|predecessor        = [[Annika Linde]]\n|deputy             = \n|birth_name= Nils Anders Tegnell\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|4|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Uppsala]], [[Sweden]]\n|nationality  = {{flag|Sweden|name=Swedish}}\n|occupation    = \n|profession    = Physician,<br/>epidemiologist,<br/>civil servant\n|alma_mater    = [[Link\u00f6ping University]]\n}}\n'''Nils Anders Tegnell''' (born 17 April 1956)<ref>''Sveriges befolkning 1980'', CD-ROM, version 1.00 (Sveriges Sl\u00e4ktforskarf\u00f6rbund 2004).</ref> is a Swedish [[physician]] and [[civil servant]]. Tegnell has served as State [[Epidemiology|Epidemiologist]] of the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] since 2013. In this position, he has a key role in the response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vem \u00e4r Anders Tegnell och vad g\u00f6r en statsepidemiolog? |url=https://www.mabra.com/vem-ar-anders-tegnell-och-vad-gor-en-statsepidemiolog/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=M\u00e5Bra |date=20 March 2020 |language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=TT |first1=Johan Nilsson / |title=Tegnell svarar p\u00e5 norsk kritik: \u201dG\u00f6r det l\u00e4tt f\u00f6r sig\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/anders-tegnell-svarar-pa-den-norska-kritiken |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Svenska Dagbladet |date=27 March 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTegnell was born in [[Uppsala]]. He became a licensed physician at [[Lund University]] in 1985 and specialised in [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious disease]]. He later worked for the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] in [[Laos]] to create [[vaccination program]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delin |first1=Mikael |title=Statsepidemiolog Anders Tegnell: Sverige har v\u00e4ldigt sv\u00e5rt att acceptera risker |url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/statsepidemiolog-anders-tegnell-sverige-har-valdigt-svart-att-acceptera-risker/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Expressen]]'', he describes his on-site work for the WHO with a Swedish expert team during the [[List of Ebola outbreaks|1995 Ebola outbreak in Kikwit, Zaire]] as a formative experience.<ref>{{cite news |last1=B\u00f6rjesson |first1=Robert |title=Ok\u00e4nda tragedin som formade Anders Tegnell |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/qs/okanda-tragedin-som-formade-anders-tegnell/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Expressen]] |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> \nTegnell obtained a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Medicine]] from [[Link\u00f6ping University]] in 2003 and a [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Epidemiology from the [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]] in 2004.<ref name=anderson>{{cite book| |last=Anderson |first= Bj\u00f6rn |title=Kungl Krigsvetenskapsakademien. Svenska Krigsmanna S\u00e4llskapet (till 1805), Kungl Krigsvetenskapsakademien. 20 \u00e5r med akademien och dess ledam\u00f6ter 1996\u20132016 |year=2016 |publisher=Kungliga Krigsvetenskapsakademien |location=Stockholm |isbn=978-91-980878-8-8 |pages=61 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Tegnell |first=Anders |title=The epidemiology and consequences of wound infections caused by coagulase negative staphylococci after thoracic surgery |year=2002 |publisher=[[Link\u00f6ping University]] |location=Link\u00f6ping |isbn=91-7373-186-2 }}.</ref> He worked at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control (''Smittskyddsinstitutet'') 2004\u20132005 and the [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] from 2005,<ref name=anderson/> 2010 to 2012 serving as head of the Department for Knowledge-Based Policy.<ref name=anderson/><ref>{{cite book|title=Sveriges statskalender 2010 |year=2010 |publisher=Fritzes |location=Stockholm |pages=254 }}.</ref> He was department head at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control 2012\u20132013. Since 2013 he is the State Epidemiologist of Sweden,<ref name=anderson/> first at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control, which in 2014 became part of the Public Health Agency of Sweden.\n\nAnders Tegnell was elected member of the [[Royal Swedish Academy of War Sciences]] in 2005.<ref name=anderson/> His inaugural lecture was on the effect of [[pandemic]]s on society.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pandemiernas p\u00e5verkan p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llet |url=https://kkrva.se/wp-content/uploads/Artiklar/075/kkrvaht_5_2007_6.pdf |year=2007 |journal=Kungl. Krigsvetenskapsakademiens handlingar och tidskrift |volume=5/2007 |pages=76\u201379 |first=Anders |last=Tegnell}}</ref>\n\n==2009 vaccination policy controversy==\nAnders has been criticized for his role in the mass vaccination scheme of 5 million Swedes. Pandemrix an vaccine for Swine Flu that has been to known to cause neurological issues and which did cause about 500 patients to suffer from narcolepsy. https://engnews24h.com/tegnell-defends-vaccination-that-gave-500-young-swedes-narcolepsy/ \n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tegnell, Anders}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish civil servants]]\n[[Category:Swedish epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Uppsala]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Swedish Academy of War Sciences]]\n[[Category:Link\u00f6ping University alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish infectious disease physicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Lund University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Swedish physician and civil servant}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name               = Anders Tegnell\n|image              = \n|office             = State [[Epidemiologist]] of the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]]\n|term_start         = 2013\n|predecessor        = [[Annika Linde]]\n|deputy             = \n|birth_name= Nils Anders Tegnell\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|4|17|df=yes}}\n|birth_place  = [[Uppsala]], [[Sweden]]\n|nationality  = {{flag|Sweden|name=Swedish}}\n|occupation    = \n|profession    = Physician,<br/>epidemiologist,<br/>civil servant\n|alma_mater    = [[Link\u00f6ping University]]\n}}\n'''Nils Anders Tegnell''' (born 17 April 1956 in [[Uppsala]])<ref>''Sveriges befolkning 1980'', CD-ROM, version 1.00 (Sveriges Sl\u00e4ktforskarf\u00f6rbund 2004).</ref> is a Swedish [[physician]] and [[civil servant]]. Tegnell has served as State [[Epidemiology|Epidemiologist]] of the [[Public Health Agency of Sweden]] since 2013. In this position, he has a key role in the response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Sweden]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Vem \u00e4r Anders Tegnell och vad g\u00f6r en statsepidemiolog? |url=https://www.mabra.com/vem-ar-anders-tegnell-och-vad-gor-en-statsepidemiolog/ |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=M\u00e5Bra |date=20 March 2020 |language=sv-SE}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=TT |first1=Johan Nilsson / |title=Tegnell svarar p\u00e5 norsk kritik: \u201dG\u00f6r det l\u00e4tt f\u00f6r sig\u201d |url=https://www.svd.se/anders-tegnell-svarar-pa-den-norska-kritiken |accessdate=27 March 2020 |work=Svenska Dagbladet |date=27 March 2020 |language=sv}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nTegnell became a licensed physician at [[Lund University]] in 1985 and specialised in [[Infectious disease (medical specialty)|infectious disease]]. He later worked for the [[World Health Organization|WHO]] in [[Laos]] to create [[vaccination program]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Delin |first1=Mikael |title=Statsepidemiolog Anders Tegnell: Sverige har v\u00e4ldigt sv\u00e5rt att acceptera risker |url=https://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/statsepidemiolog-anders-tegnell-sverige-har-valdigt-svart-att-acceptera-risker/ |accessdate=24 March 2020 |work=[[Dagens Nyheter]] |date=11 March 2020}}</ref> In an interview with ''[[Expressen]]'', he describes his on-site work for the WHO with a Swedish expert team during the [[List of Ebola outbreaks|1995 Ebola outbreak in Kikwit, Zaire]] as a formative experience.<ref>{{cite news |last1=B\u00f6rjesson |first1=Robert |title=Ok\u00e4nda tragedin som formade Anders Tegnell |url=https://www.expressen.se/nyheter/qs/okanda-tragedin-som-formade-anders-tegnell/ |accessdate=2 April 2020 |work=[[Expressen]] |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> \nTegnell obtained a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] in [[Medicine]] from [[Link\u00f6ping University]] in 2003 and a [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Epidemiology from the [[London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine]] in 2004.<ref name=anderson>{{cite book| |last=Anderson |first= Bj\u00f6rn |title=Kungl Krigsvetenskapsakademien. Svenska Krigsmanna S\u00e4llskapet (till 1805), Kungl Krigsvetenskapsakademien. 20 \u00e5r med akademien och dess ledam\u00f6ter 1996\u20132016 |year=2016 |publisher=Kungliga Krigsvetenskapsakademien |location=Stockholm |isbn=978-91-980878-8-8 |pages=61 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Tegnell |first=Anders |title=The epidemiology and consequences of wound infections caused by coagulase negative staphylococci after thoracic surgery |year=2002 |publisher=[[Link\u00f6ping University]] |location=Link\u00f6ping |isbn=91-7373-186-2 }}.</ref> He worked at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control (''Smittskyddsinstitutet'') 2004\u20132005 and the [[National Board of Health and Welfare (Sweden)|National Board of Health and Welfare]] from 2005,<ref name=anderson/> 2010 to 2012 serving as head of the Department for Knowledge-Based Policy.<ref name=anderson/><ref>{{cite book|title=Sveriges statskalender 2010 |year=2010 |publisher=Fritzes |location=Stockholm |pages=254 }}.</ref> He was department head at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control 2012\u20132013. Since 2013 he is the State Epidemiologist of Sweden,<ref name=anderson/> first at the Swedish Institute for Communicable Disease Control, which in 2014 became part of the Public Health Agency of Sweden.\n\nAnders Tegnell was elected member of the [[Royal Swedish Academy of War Sciences]] in 2005.<ref name=anderson/> His inaugural lecture was on the effect of [[pandemic]]s on society.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Pandemiernas p\u00e5verkan p\u00e5 samh\u00e4llet |url=https://kkrva.se/wp-content/uploads/Artiklar/075/kkrvaht_5_2007_6.pdf |year=2007 |journal=Kungl. Krigsvetenskapsakademiens handlingar och tidskrift |volume=5/2007 |pages=76\u201379 |first=Anders |last=Tegnell}}</ref>\n\n==2009 vaccination policy controversy==\nAnders has been criticized for his role in the mass vaccination scheme of 5 million Swedes. Pandemrix an vaccine for Swine Flu that has been to known to cause neurological issues and which did cause about 500 patients to suffer from narcolepsy. https://engnews24h.com/tegnell-defends-vaccination-that-gave-500-young-swedes-narcolepsy/ \n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tegnell, Anders}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish civil servants]]\n[[Category:Swedish epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Uppsala]]\n[[Category:Members of the Royal Swedish Academy of War Sciences]]\n[[Category:Link\u00f6ping University alumni]]\n[[Category:Swedish infectious disease physicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Lund University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "bring intro into line with bio standards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anders_Tegnell"}
{"title_page": "Nikon Museum", "text_new": "{{copyedit|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox Museum\n  |name        = NIKON MUSEUM\n  |image       = Nikon Museum20151104a.jpg\n  |established = 2015 October 17\n  |location    = [[Shinagawa, Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n  |owner       = [[Nikon|Nikon Corporation]]\n  |type        = [[Industrial Museum]]\n  |visitors    =\n  |director    =\n  |website     = [http://www.nikon.co.jp/profile/museum/]\n}}\n\n'''[[Nikon]] Museum''' is a museum of [[Nikon]] products, located at [[Shinagawa, Tokyo]], [[Japan]], in the same location as the  Nikon headquarters.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Nikon Museum opened in July 2017 to commemorate [[Nikon]]'s 100th anniversary.  It is the first facility to showcase a number of optical products and technologies from the firm.<ref name=\"impress\">[http://dc.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/20151001_723666.html \u30ab\u30e1\u30e9450\u53f0\u3092\u5c55\u793a\u3059\u308b\u300c\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u300117\u65e5\u306b\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3]</ref> The museum occupies 580 square meters, and displays a range of historical Nikon cameras, microscopes, measuring instruments, and equipment for semiconductor [[photolithography]].<ref name=\"impress\"/><ref name=\"jcast\">[http://www.j-cast.com/2015/11/03249164.html \u30b9\u30de\u30db\u3067\u7e2e\u5c0f\u3059\u308b\u30c7\u30b8\u30ab\u30e1\u5e02\u5834\u3067\u65e5\u672c\u30d6\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u306f\u751f\u304d\u6b8b\u308c\u308b\u304b \u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u3001\u5275\u696d100\u5e74\u3067\u4f01\u696d\u300c\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3]</ref> The museum is the first of its type in Japan.<ref name = \"jcast\" /> [[Nikon]] has developed a range of digital cameras that are used by professionals. The Museum's stated purpose by one Nikon official is to \"protect the brand...[and] put out a new product that seems attractive.\"<ref name=\"jcast\"/>\n\n==Opening Hours==\nUnder normal circumstances, the Museum is open on weekdays, and admission is free. Due to global concern regarding the spread of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19), the Museum is temporarily closed.<ref>https://www.nikon.com/about/corporate/museum/</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lenstip.com/141.1-article-A_visit_in_the_Nikon_Museum_in_Japan.html|title=A Visit in the Nikon Museum in Japan|last=Olech|first=Robert|date=1 August 2017|website=LensTip|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nikon.com/about/corporate/museum/exhibitions/|title=Nikon {{!}} Nikon Museum {{!}} Exhibitions|website=www.nikon.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>==\n;A Century at Nikon \u5149\u3068\u7cbe\u5bc6\u3001100\u5e74\u306e\u8db3\u8de1\n:Introduces the history of Nikon from its inception in 1917 to present times on a wall.\n;Synthetic Silica Glass Ingot\n:A silica glass ingot as long as 130cm, shaped like a lens tube, is an embodiment of the Nikon Museum and represents the materials used for the production of its top-of-the-line optics during the last 100 years. There is a plaque next to the ingot with the inscription \"Please touch\".\n;Theater \u6620\u50cf\u3068\u97f3\u697d\u3067\u632f\u308a\u8fd4\u308b\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u306e100\u5e74\n:To [[:ja:\u548c\u7530\u85ab]] orchestra playing who led his own Wada the Symphony was composed, To screening a video that interweaves the history and products of Nikon.\n;Lens Laboratory \u30ec\u30f3\u30ba\u306e\u5b9f\u9a13\u5ba4\n:A small room where the most important technologies used in Nikon lenses are presented, such as anti-reflective coatings and the methods used to deal with distortions and chromatic aberration.\n;Spirit of Nikon \u6b21\u306e100\u5e74\u3078\u3001\u53d7\u3051\u7d99\u304c\u308c\u308b\u7cbe\u795e\n:An exhibition displaying items that showcase the technical heritage and roots behind the first century of Nikon.\n;Feature Showcase\n:News camera, prototype camera, photo image electrical transmission equipment, binoculars, eyeglass lenses, etc. exhibition.\n;Imaging\n:From \"Nikon I type\" to the latest digital single-lens reflex camera, display the camera and the lens of about 450 points under one roof.<ref name=\"digimono\">[http://www.digimonostation.jp/0000036371/ 100\u5e74\u306e\u5149\u5b66\u6280\u8853\u306b\u5727\u5012\u3055\u308c\u308b\u300c\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u30ec\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8]</ref> Related episodes and technology commentary.\n;Industry\n:Semiconductor manufacturing equipment and exhibition of measurement equipment.Operating demonstration of the reduction projection type exposure apparatus used in semiconductor manufacturing is observed.\n;Bioscience and Medical Imaging\n:An exhibit showcasing Nikon's involvement in healthcare and medical fields. Displayed items include microscopes, medical imaging devices, and bio-stations used in medical laboratories.\n;Space\n:A wall emphasizing the role that Nikon played in the conquest and subsequent research of outer space.\n\n'''Nikon in Motion'''\n\n:A small room with historical Nikkor lenses. Includes a movie, \"Made by Nikon\", presenting the stories behind Nikon employees and workers all over the world.\n\n<br /><gallery>\nFile:Nikon Museum20151104b.jpg|Synthetic quartz glass ingot developed for semiconductor exposure equipment.\nFile:Nikon Museum20151104c.jpg|Exhibit of about 450 models of Nikon cameras.\n</gallery>\n\n== '''Nikon Museum Special Collection''' ==\n\n==== '''Special Exhibition \"Nikon Museum Special Collection\"''' ====\n[[File:1.5_m_Rangefinder_1936.jpg|thumb|https://redbook-jp.com/]]\nDates :\u00a0 April 2, 2019 (Tue) - June 29, 2019 (Sat)\n\nPlace :\u00a0 Nikon Museum, Shinagawa Tokyo\n\nExhibits :\u00a0 Approx. 30 items including cameras, measuring instruments and industrial equipment \u00a0 \u00a0 \"EYES OF SCIENCE\" movie\n\nNikon Museum houses approximately 40,000 materials spanning Nikon's 100-year history. Nikon Museum is holding the \"Nikon Museum Special Collection\" from April 2 to June 29, 2019. Michio Akiyama of the Nikon Kenkyukai member visited the Nikon museum on 2rd April of the opening date of the special exhibition.This special exhibition comprises approximately 30 items that include products released between the 1930's and 1990's. \u00a0 This is a very rare exhibition that illustrates heretofore unknown aspects of Nikon's history through materials from a wide range of categories such as cameras, measuring instruments and industrial equipment. \u00a0 In addition, the movie \"EYES OF SCIENCE\", produced by Nikon (then Nippon Kogaku) in 1966, will be continuously played on a special screen.[https://redbook-jp.com/kenkyukai-e/2019/201904.html]\n\n\n==Museum shop==\nA small museum shop is located at the side entrance.<ref name=\"digimono\"/> Some merchandise items include camera-patterned playing cards, drinking tumblers in the shape of lenses, [[:ja:\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u3088\u3046\u304b\u3093|Yokan]] and more.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nikon Museum}}\n*{{official website|www.nikon.com/about/info/museum/}}\n\n{{coord missing|Japan}}\n\n[[Category:Nikon]]\n[[Category:Museums in Japan]]\n", "text_old": "{{copyedit|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox Museum\n  |name        = NIKON MUSEUM\n  |image       = Nikon Museum20151104a.jpg\n  |established = 2015 October 17\n  |location    = [[Shinagawa, Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n  |owner       = [[Nikon|Nikon Corporation]]\n  |type        = [[Industrial Museum]]\n  |visitors    =\n  |director    =\n  |website     = [http://www.nikon.co.jp/profile/museum/]\n}}\n\n'''[[Nikon]] Museum''' is a museum of [[Nikon]] products, located at [[Shinagawa, Tokyo]], [[Japan]], in the same location as the  Nikon headquarters.\n\n==Overview==\nThe Nikon Museum opened in July 2017 to commemorate [[Nikon]]'s 100th anniversary.  It is the first facility to showcase a number of optical products and technologies from the firm.<ref name=\"impress\">[http://dc.watch.impress.co.jp/docs/news/20151001_723666.html \u30ab\u30e1\u30e9450\u53f0\u3092\u5c55\u793a\u3059\u308b\u300c\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u300117\u65e5\u306b\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3]</ref> The museum occupies 580 square meters, and displays a range of historical Nikon cameras, microscopes, measuring instruments, and equipment for semiconductor [[photolithography]].<ref name=\"impress\"/><ref name=\"jcast\">[http://www.j-cast.com/2015/11/03249164.html \u30b9\u30de\u30db\u3067\u7e2e\u5c0f\u3059\u308b\u30c7\u30b8\u30ab\u30e1\u5e02\u5834\u3067\u65e5\u672c\u30d6\u30e9\u30f3\u30c9\u306f\u751f\u304d\u6b8b\u308c\u308b\u304b \u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u3001\u5275\u696d100\u5e74\u3067\u4f01\u696d\u300c\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30f3]</ref> The museum is the first of its type in Japan.<ref name = \"jcast\" /> [[Nikon]] has developed a range of digital cameras that are used by professionals. The Museum's stated purpose by one Nikon official is to \"protect the brand...[and] put out a new product that seems attractive.\"<ref name=\"jcast\"/>\n\n==Opening Hours==\nUnder normal circumstances, the Museum is open on weekdays, and admission is free. Due to global concern regarding the spread of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19), the Museum is temporarily closed.<ref>https://www.nikon.com/about/corporate/museum/</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lenstip.com/141.1-article-A_visit_in_the_Nikon_Museum_in_Japan.html|title=A Visit in the Nikon Museum in Japan|last=Olech|first=Robert|date=1 August 2017|website=LensTip|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nikon.com/about/corporate/museum/exhibitions/|title=Nikon {{!}} Nikon Museum {{!}} Exhibitions|website=www.nikon.com|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>==\n;A Century at Nikon \u5149\u3068\u7cbe\u5bc6\u3001100\u5e74\u306e\u8db3\u8de1\n:Introduces the history of Nikon from its inception in 1917 to present times on a wall.\n;Synthetic Silica Glass Ingot\n:A silica glass ingot as long as 130cm, shaped like a lens tube, is an embodiment of the Nikon Museum and represents the materials used for the production of its top-of-the-line optics during the last 100 years. There is a plaque next to the ingot with the inscription \"Please touch\".\n;Theater \u6620\u50cf\u3068\u97f3\u697d\u3067\u632f\u308a\u8fd4\u308b\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u306e100\u5e74\n:To [[:ja:\u548c\u7530\u85ab]] orchestra playing who led his own Wada the Symphony was composed, To screening a video that interweaves the history and products of Nikon.\n;Lens Laboratory \u30ec\u30f3\u30ba\u306e\u5b9f\u9a13\u5ba4\n:A small room where the most important technologies used in Nikon lenses are presented, such as anti-reflective coatings and the methods used to deal with distortions and chromatic aberration.\n;Spirit of Nikon \u6b21\u306e100\u5e74\u3078\u3001\u53d7\u3051\u7d99\u304c\u308c\u308b\u7cbe\u795e\n:An exhibition displaying items that showcase the technical heritage and roots behind the first century of Nikon.\n;Feature Showcase\n:News camera, prototype camera, photo image electrical transmission equipment, binoculars, eyeglass lenses, etc. exhibition.\n;Imaging\n:From \"Nikon I type\" to the latest digital single-lens reflex camera, display the camera and the lens of about 450 points under one roof.<ref name=\"digimono\">[http://www.digimonostation.jp/0000036371/ 100\u5e74\u306e\u5149\u5b66\u6280\u8853\u306b\u5727\u5012\u3055\u308c\u308b\u300c\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u30df\u30e5\u30fc\u30b8\u30a2\u30e0\u300d\u30ec\u30dd\u30fc\u30c8]</ref> Related episodes and technology commentary.\n;Industry\n:Semiconductor manufacturing equipment and exhibition of measurement equipment.Operating demonstration of the reduction projection type exposure apparatus used in semiconductor manufacturing is observed.\n;Bioscience and Medical Imaging\n:An exhibit showcasing Nikon's involvement in healthcare and medical fields. Displayed items include microscopes, medical imaging devices, and bio-stations used in medical laboratories.\n;Space\n:A wall emphasizing the role that Nikon played in the conquest and subsequent research of outer space.\n\n'''Nikon in Motion'''\n\n:A small room with historical Nikkor lenses. Includes a movie, \"Made by Nikon\", presenting the stories behind Nikon employees and workers all over the world.\n\n<br /><gallery>\nFile:Nikon Museum20151104b.jpg|Synthetic quartz glass ingot developed for semiconductor exposure equipment.\nFile:Nikon Museum20151104c.jpg|Exhibit of about 450 models of Nikon cameras.\n</gallery>\n\n\n==Museum shop==\nA small museum shop is located at the side entrance.<ref name=\"digimono\"/> Some merchandise items include camera-patterned playing cards, drinking tumblers in the shape of lenses, [[:ja:\u30cb\u30b3\u30f3\u3088\u3046\u304b\u3093|Yokan]] and more.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nikon Museum}}\n*{{official website|www.nikon.com/about/info/museum/}}\n\n{{coord missing|Japan}}\n\n[[Category:Nikon]]\n[[Category:Museums in Japan]]\n", "name_user": "Trustyeditor", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added Special Exhibition \"Nikon Museum Special Collection\" information", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nikon_Museum"}
{"title_page": "Naika Foroutan", "text_new": "{{Infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL  }}\n\n'''Naika Foroutan''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0641\u0631\u0648\u062a\u0646}}; born 24 December 1971<ref name=\"kurzbiographie\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Naika Foroutan|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan/kurzbio_foroutan|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319214726/http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan/kurzbio_foroutan|archivedate=2011-03-19|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> in [[Boppard]]<ref>{{cite web|title=1. Bundesfachkongress Interkultur 2006 in Stuttgart. Referentenliste|periodical=bundesfachkongress-interkultur.de|publisher=|url=http://www.bundesfachkongress-interkultur.de/2006/referenten.html|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>) is a German social scientist.\n\nShe has been head of the research group \"Young Islam-related topics in Germany\" (JUNITED) at the Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t Berlin (HU) since 2011; in June 2015, she was appointed professor of \"integration research and social policy\" by Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t.<ref>Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung (BIM): [http://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/ ''Prof. '']</ref> In addition, she is secretary of the five-member board of the German Council for Migration;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rat-fuer-migration.de/ueber-uns/vorstand/|title=Vorstand|date=18 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> since 2017 she has also been head of the German Centre for Integration and Migration Research (DeZIM).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezim-institut.de/das-dezim-institut/|title=Das DeZIM-Institut \u2013 DeZIM-Institut|website=www.dezim-institut.de|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2018, Foroutan has been the director of the Berlin Institute for Empirical Integration and Migration Research (BIM) and has led the \"Integration research and social policy\" department.<ref>{{cite web|title=Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung - Prof. Dr. Naika Foroutan|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/|format=|accessdate=2018-06-28|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=BIM|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=de-DE|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nForoutan is the daughter of a German mother and an Iranian father. She is the sister of actress [[Melika Foroutan]]. Her father Bahman Foroutan is a football coach. He was from 2010 to 2014, coach of various amateur clubs in Berlin. Naika Foroutan lived for 11 years in Tehran and left Iran in 1983 together with her family.<ref name=\"books-NBZ2N3mGM74C-PR11\">Naika Foroutan: ''Kulturdialoge zwischen dem Westen und der islamischen Welt: eine Strategie zur Regulierung von Zivilisationskonflikten'', Vorwort.</ref> Foroutan studied political science, romance Philology and Islamic Studies at the [[University of Cologne]]. In the years 2000 to 2004 she received a doctorate at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]] at Bassam Tibi in the thematic area \"inter-civilisation cultural dialogues between the West and the Islamic world\" as a result, she was there as a lecturer in the field International relations. Between 2006 and 2009, Foroutan taught at the Department of Politics of the Middle East at the Otto-Suhr-Institut of the [[Free University of Berlin|Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin]], until she then switched to the Institute for Social Sciences of the [[Humboldt University Berlin|Humboldt University of Berlin]]. From 2008 to 2013, together with her colleague [[Isabel Sch\u00e4fer]], she led the research project \"hybrid European-Muslim identity models (HEYMAT)\". The HEYMAT project was extended to 2013 by the Volkswagen Foundation until the year 2015. Since the extension, Naika Foroutan has led the HEYMAT project. The HEYMAT project was completed at the end of June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/projekte/2008/04/01/2015/06/01/hybride-europaeisch-muslimische-identitaetsmodelle-heymat/|title=Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung - Hybride europ\u00e4isch-muslimische Identit\u00e4tsmodelle (HEYMAT)|first=|last=BIM|website=www.bim.hu-berlin.de|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn cooperation with the Mercator Foundation, Foroutan organized the \"Young Islam conference-Berlin 2011\" for the Humboldt University in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Junge Islam Konferenz \u2014 Heymat|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/junge-islamkonferenz|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=2013-10-15|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> In the year 2012, another \"young Islam conference\" was held under her leadership. During the conference it was announced that the \"Young Islam Conference\" and a corresponding research project \"Young Islam-related issues in Germany\"  under Foroutans, would continue up to the year 2016, with two million euros funding by the&nbsp;Mercator foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zwei Millionen Euro f\u00fcr die Junge Islam Konferenz|periodical=hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.hu-berlin.de/pr/pressemitteilungen/pm1204/pm_120423_00|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=2012-04-19|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> Since 2012, she is co-head of the research project \"Concepts for the development of intelligence, Security and Prevention\" (CODISP), sponsored by the Federal Ministry of Education and Research.<ref name=\"teamforoutan\">{{cite web|title=Naika Foroutan \u2014 Heymat|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Naika Foroutan}}\n* [https://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/ Foroutans Profil] auf der Seite der HU Berlin\n* [[Goethe-Institut]], 2012, Interview von Britta Mersch: [http://de.qantara.de/Junge-Muslime-moechten-das-Land-mitgestalten/19636c20886i1p498/index.html de.qantara.de: ''Junge Muslime m\u00f6chten das Land mitgestalten''.]\n* [[Der Tagesspiegel|Tagesspiegel.de]], 22. Juli 2018, Interview von Andrea Dernbach: [https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/migrationsforscherin-naika-foroutan-es-ist-unser-land-verteidigen-wir-es-gemeinsam/22830476.html ''\"Es ist unser Land, verteidigen wir es gemeinsam\"'']\n{{CC-notice|cc=bysa3|url=https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naika_Foroutan }}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foroutan, Naika}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Free University of Berlin faculty]]\n[[Category:Humboldt University of Berlin faculty]]\n[[Category:German political scientists]]\n[[Category:German social scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Cologne alumni]]\n[[Category:Women political scientists]]\n[[Category:Women social scientists]]\n[[Category:People from Rhein-Hunsr\u00fcck-Kreis]]\n[[Category:German people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person/Wikidata | fetchwikidata=ALL  }}\n\n'''Naika Foroutan''' ({{Lang-fa|\u0646\u0627\u06cc\u06a9\u0627 \u0641\u0631\u0648\u062a\u0646}}; born 24 December 1971<ref name=\"kurzbiographie\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Naika Foroutan|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan/kurzbio_foroutan|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319214726/http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan/kurzbio_foroutan|archivedate=2011-03-19|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> in [[Boppard]]<ref>{{cite web|title=1. Bundesfachkongress Interkultur 2006 in Stuttgart. Referentenliste|periodical=bundesfachkongress-interkultur.de|publisher=|url=http://www.bundesfachkongress-interkultur.de/2006/referenten.html|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>) is a German social scientist.\n\nSince 2011 she is head of the research group \"Young Islam-related topics in Germany\" (junited) at the Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t Berlin (HU); In June 2015, she was appointed professor of \"Integration research and Social policy\" by Humboldt-Universit\u00e4t.<ref>Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung (BIM): [http://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/ ''Prof. '']</ref> In addition, she is secretary of the five-member board of the German Council for Migration;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rat-fuer-migration.de/ueber-uns/vorstand/|title=Vorstand|date=18 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref> Since 2017 also head of the \"German Centre for Integration and Migration Research\" (DeZIM).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dezim-institut.de/das-dezim-institut/|title=Das DeZIM-Institut \u2013 DeZIM-Institut|website=www.dezim-institut.de|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince May 2018, Foroutan is the director of the \"Berlin Institute for Empirical Integration and Migration research\" (BIM) and is head of the \"Integration research and social policy\" working area.<ref>{{cite web|title=Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung - Prof. Dr. Naika Foroutan|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/|format=|accessdate=2018-06-28|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=BIM|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=de-DE|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nForoutan is the daughter of a German mother and an Iranian father. She is the sister of actress [[Melika Foroutan]]. Her father Bahman Foroutan is a football coach. He was from 2010 to 2014, coach of various amateur clubs in Berlin. Naika Foroutan lived for 11 years in Tehran and left Iran in 1983 together with her family.<ref name=\"books-NBZ2N3mGM74C-PR11\">Naika Foroutan: ''Kulturdialoge zwischen dem Westen und der islamischen Welt: eine Strategie zur Regulierung von Zivilisationskonflikten'', Vorwort.</ref> Foroutan studied political science, romance Philology and Islamic Studies at the [[University of Cologne]]. In the years 2000 to 2004 she received a doctorate at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]] at Bassam Tibi in the thematic area \"inter-civilisation cultural dialogues between the West and the Islamic world\" as a result, she was there as a lecturer in the field International relations. Between 2006 and 2009, Foroutan taught at the Department of Politics of the Middle East at the Otto-Suhr-Institut of the [[Free University of Berlin|Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin]], until she then switched to the Institute for Social Sciences of the [[Humboldt University Berlin|Humboldt University of Berlin]]. From 2008 to 2013, together with her colleague [[Isabel Sch\u00e4fer]], she led the research project \"hybrid European-Muslim identity models (HEYMAT)\". The HEYMAT project was extended to 2013 by the Volkswagen Foundation until the year 2015. Since the extension, Naika Foroutan has led the HEYMAT project. The HEYMAT project was completed at the end of June 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/projekte/2008/04/01/2015/06/01/hybride-europaeisch-muslimische-identitaetsmodelle-heymat/|title=Berliner Institut f\u00fcr empirische Integrations- und Migrationsforschung - Hybride europ\u00e4isch-muslimische Identit\u00e4tsmodelle (HEYMAT)|first=|last=BIM|website=www.bim.hu-berlin.de|accessdate=25 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn cooperation with the Mercator Foundation, Foroutan organized the \"Young Islam conference-Berlin 2011\" for the Humboldt University in Berlin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Junge Islam Konferenz \u2014 Heymat|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/junge-islamkonferenz|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=2013-10-15|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> In the year 2012, another \"young Islam conference\" was held under her leadership. During the conference it was announced that the \"Young Islam Conference\" and a corresponding research project \"Young Islam-related issues in Germany\"  under Foroutans, would continue up to the year 2016, with two million euros funding by the&nbsp;Mercator foundation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Zwei Millionen Euro f\u00fcr die Junge Islam Konferenz|periodical=hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.hu-berlin.de/pr/pressemitteilungen/pm1204/pm_120423_00|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=2012-04-19|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref> Since 2012, she is co-head of the research project \"Concepts for the development of intelligence, Security and Prevention\" (CODISP), sponsored by the Federal Ministry of Education and Research.<ref name=\"teamforoutan\">{{cite web|title=Naika Foroutan \u2014 Heymat|periodical=heymat.hu-berlin.de|publisher=|url=http://www.heymat.hu-berlin.de/team/foroutan|format=|accessdate=2015-02-17|archiveurl=|archivedate=|last=|date=|year=|month=|day=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Naika Foroutan}}\n* [https://www.bim.hu-berlin.de/de/personen/prof-dr-naika-foroutan/ Foroutans Profil] auf der Seite der HU Berlin\n* [[Goethe-Institut]], 2012, Interview von Britta Mersch: [http://de.qantara.de/Junge-Muslime-moechten-das-Land-mitgestalten/19636c20886i1p498/index.html de.qantara.de: ''Junge Muslime m\u00f6chten das Land mitgestalten''.]\n* [[Der Tagesspiegel|Tagesspiegel.de]], 22. Juli 2018, Interview von Andrea Dernbach: [https://www.tagesspiegel.de/politik/migrationsforscherin-naika-foroutan-es-ist-unser-land-verteidig